54. Inheritance
one class acquiring the properties of another basically child from parent
Inheritance allows a child class to acquire properties and methods from a parent class, promoting code reusability.

types: 
single- single child and single parent             
A → B
multilevel - parent child subchild                 
A → B -> C
multiple - multiple parents single child
  A   B
   \ /
    C

Parent A: Clock (time())    Parent B: FitnessTracker (pulse())
                  \          /
                   └── Child: Smartwatch (uses both)

hierarchial - multiple childs acquiring properties from same single parent

     A
   /   \
  B     C

 Parent: Animal (Properties: eat(), sleep())
         /         |         \
Child: Dog    Child: Cat    Child: Cow
(bark())      (meow())      (moo())


hybrid - both multiple and hierarchial
 A    B
   \ /
    C
   / \
D      C 

             Base Parent: Vehicle
             /                    \
   Parent A: Car                Parent B: Boat
             \                    /
       Child: AmphibiousVehicle (Hybrid)


1. Single Inheritance
# Parent Class
class Animal:
    def eat(self):
        return "Eating food..."

# Child Class inheriting from Animal
class Dog(Animal):
    def bark(self):
        return "Woof!"

# Usage
my_dog = Dog()
print(my_dog.eat())  # Inherited method -> "Eating food..."
print(my_dog.bark()) # Child method -> "Woof!"

2. Multilevel Inheritance
# Grandparent Class
class Vehicle:
    def start(self):
        return "Vehicle started."

# Parent Class inheriting from Vehicle
class Car(Vehicle):
    def drive(self):
        return "Car is moving."

# Child Class inheriting from Car
class ElectricCar(Car):
    def charge(self):
        return "Battery charging..."

# Usage
tesla = ElectricCar()
print(tesla.start())  # From Grandparent -> "Vehicle started."
print(tesla.drive())  # From Parent -> "Car is moving."
print(tesla.charge()) # From Child -> "Battery charging..."

3. Multiple Inheritance
# Parent Class 1
class Flyer:
    def fly(self):
        return "Flying high!"

# Parent Class 2
class Swimmer:
    def swim(self):
        return "Swimming fast!"

# Child Class inheriting from BOTH Parent Classes
class Duck(Flyer, Swimmer):
    def quack(self):
        return "Quack!"

# Usage
donald = Duck()
print(donald.fly())   # From Flyer -> "Flying high!"
print(donald.swim())  # From Swimmer -> "Swimming fast!"
print(donald.quack()) # From Duck -> "Quack!"

4. Hierarchical Inheritance
# Shared Parent Class
class Staff:
    def log_in(self):
        return "Logged into system."

# Child Class 1
class Doctor(Staff):
    def treat_patient(self):
        return "Treating patient..."

# Child Class 2
class Nurse(Staff):
    def give_medicine(self):
        return "Administering medicine..."

# Usage
doc = Doctor()
nurse = Nurse()
print(doc.log_in())        # From Staff -> "Logged into system."
print(doc.treat_patient()) # From Doctor -> "Treating patient..."
print(nurse.log_in())      # From Staff -> "Logged into system."
print(nurse.give_medicine()) # From Nurse -> "Administering medicine..."

5. Hybrid Inheritance
# Base Parent Class
class School:
    def school_info(self):
        return "Welcome to School."

# Hierarchical split from School
class Teacher(School):
    def teach(self):
        return "Teaching students..."

class Student(School):
    def study(self):
        return "Studying lessons..."

# Multiple inheritance combination (combines Teacher and Student)
class TeachingAssistant(Teacher, Student):
    def assist(self):
        return "Assisting grading..."

# Usage
ta = TeachingAssistant()
print(ta.school_info()) # From School (Grandparent) -> "Welcome to School."
print(ta.teach())       # From Teacher (Parent 1) -> "Teaching students..."
print(ta.study())       # From Student (Parent 2) -> "Studying lessons..."
print(ta.assist())      # From TeachingAssistant -> "Assisting grading..."

56. Polymorphism - Polymorphism refers to the ability of code, data, or objects to take on multiple forms
Polymorphism in Python is a core Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) concept that allows a single interface, function, or operator to behave differently depending on the object or data type it acts upon
Polymorphism means "many forms" and allows the same method, function or operator to behave differently depending on the object or data it works with

Compile-Time Polymorphism and Runtime Polymorphism :-
Both allow the same method name to be used for different tasks, but they execute at different times during program execution




57. Encapsulation?
Encapsulation is the binding of data and methods that manipulate them into a single unit such that the sensitive data is hidden from the users

It is implemented as the processes mentioned below:
Data hiding: A language feature to restrict access to members of an object. For example, private and protected members in C++.

Bundling of data and methods together: Data and methods that operate on that data are bundled together. 
For example, the data members and member methods that operate on them are wrapped into a single unit known as a class.

58. Method overloading
Method overloading means having multiple methods with the same name but different parameters (inputs) inside the same class.
class Calculator:
    # A single method that handles different numbers of inputs
    def add(self, a, b, c = 0): 
        return a + b + c
calc = Calculator()
print(calc.add(2, 3))     # Works! Outputs: 5  (c defaults to 0)
print(calc.add(2, 3, 4))  # Works! Outputs: 9

59. Method overriding
Method overriding happens when a child class changes a method it inherited from its parent class because it needs to behave differently
class Animal:
    def make_sound(self):
        print("Some generic animal sound")

class Cat(Animal):
    # Overriding the parent's method
    def make_sound(self):
        print("Meow!")
# Testing the override
my_cat = Cat()
my_cat.make_sound()  # Outputs: Meow! (Not the generic sound)


